Yes, and I usually get on it, but I don't care about it in 2019 because intcode heavily rewards over-preparation or implementation luck (moreso than the typical problem) for problems that are much easier than what's typical in past advents. This is just an extension of the issue of previous advents having some problems that are too easy to distinguish top contenders in the first 10-20 minutes -- anything which is so easy that the limiting factor is basically typing speed, where say how you get your puzzle input and how much of the problem statement you don't read means spots on the leaderboard, is not a problem that should exist beyond day 3. There's a reasonable justification for having "easy days" to avoid burnout, but really a 2-3 minute problem is dominated by so many factors that aren't problem solving, and every intcode problem has been at that level of difficulty.
